 <P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;CARP.</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The CARP is a non-contributory, defined benefit pension plan in which substantially all of Continental's
non-pilot domestic employees
(including Messrs.&nbsp;G. Hart and Laderman) were entitled to participate. During 2019, the Company contributed $635&nbsp;million to the CARP. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Effective
December&nbsp;31, 2013, the Company froze benefit accruals under the CARP for all management and administrative employees, including Messrs.&nbsp;G. Hart and Laderman.
Effective January&nbsp;1, 2014, all management and administrative employees of the Company, including the named executive officers, participate in defined contribution plans. In addition, management
employees with compensation greater than the tax-qualified plan limit, including these officers, participate in the United Airlines,&nbsp;Inc. Management Cash Direct&nbsp;&amp; Cash Match Program. The
Company's decision to freeze the CARP was part of the Company's efforts to standardize management and administrative benefits following the 2010 merger with Continental. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
CARP benefit is based on a formula that utilizes final average compensation and service while one was an eligible employee of Continental. Compensation used to determine benefits is
regular pay, which includes salary deferral elections under broad-based employee programs (such as United's 401(k) plan), but excludes bonuses, taxable income derived from group term life insurance,
payments pursuant to profit sharing plans, and any form of non-cash or incentive compensation. A limit of $170,000 is applied to each year of compensation. Final average compensation is based on the
highest consecutive five calendar years of compensation of the ten most recent calendar years of employment. The final average compensation used to calculate the frozen accrued CARP benefit for
Messrs.&nbsp;G. Hart and Laderman is $170,000. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
benefit under the CARP is calculated as (A)&nbsp;times (B), where: </FONT></P>

<UL>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>(A)</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>is
1.19% of final average compensation plus 0.45% of the final average compensation in excess of the participant's average Social Security wage base; and
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>(B)</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>is
credited service, limited to 30&nbsp;years. </FONT></DD></DL>
</UL>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Normal
retirement under the CARP is age 65, but a participant is entitled to receive a reduced benefit after attaining either age 55 with 10&nbsp;years of service or age 50 with
20&nbsp;years of service. The early retirement benefit is the same as the normal retirement benefit, but actuarially reduced from age 65 to the </FONT></P>
 <font color="??????" style="display:none;">&#8203;</font>
 <div style="margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:12pt;">
<div style="display:none;
*display:block;
margin-top:-4pt;
"></div>

<P style='font-family:arial;page-break-before:always'></p>
<!-- ZEQ.=1,SEQ=73,EFW="2241177",CP="UNITED AIRLINES HOLDINGS, INC.",DN="1",CHK=50435,FOLIO='68',FILE='DISK104:[20ZAD1.20ZAD18001]DY18001A.;20',USER='DCOMBA',CD=';9-APR-2020;08:12' -->
<A NAME="page_dy18001_1_69"> </A>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2><A HREF="#bg18001a_main_toc">Table of Contents</A></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>early
retirement age. Messrs.&nbsp;G. Hart and Laderman were eligible for early retirement as of December&nbsp;31, 2019. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
CARP benefit can be received as a single life annuity or an actuarially equivalent contingent annuity with 50%, 66<SUP>2</SUP>/<SMALL>3</SMALL>%, 75%, or 100% of the participant's payments
continuing for the life of the surviving spouse following the participant's death, or as an actuarially equivalent lump sum. The lump sum payment option is not available if the participant terminates
before being eligible for either normal or early retirement. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Frozen SERP.</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The SERP benefit originally was granted in connection with Mr.&nbsp;Laderman's employment agreement
with Continental and will be
offset by amounts paid or payable under the CARP. These benefits are not protected from bankruptcy, are subject to the rights of creditors of the Company, and are not protected by the Pension Benefit
Guaranty Corporation. Continental provided the SERP benefits to address the compensation limits under CARP and to encourage retention by enhancing the financial value of continued employment with
Continental. Mr.&nbsp;Laderman's SERP benefit was partially frozen as of December&nbsp;31, 2010 and fully frozen as of December&nbsp;31, 2013. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Payouts
under the SERP are based on final average compensation, which was frozen as of December&nbsp;31, 2010 for all SERP participants, and credited years of service, which was
frozen as of December&nbsp;31, 2013 for Mr.&nbsp;Laderman. Under the SERP, final average compensation means the greater of a specified minimum amount or the average of the participant's highest
five years of compensation during their last ten calendar years through the 2010 freeze date. For purposes of such calculation, compensation includes salary and cash bonuses but excludes certain other
award payments, such as proceeds from awards under any option or stock incentive plan and any cash awards paid under a long-term incentive plan. The final average compensation used to calculate the
frozen SERP accrued benefit is $655,357 for Mr.&nbsp;Laderman and credited years of service recognized under the SERP began January&nbsp;1, 2000 for Mr.&nbsp;Laderman. Mr.&nbsp;Laderman
received one additional credited year of service under the SERP for each actual year of service during the period 2000 through 2004. This additional service credit was provided as a retention
incentive. The portion of the Present Value of Accumulated Benefits attributable to years of service credited under the SERP that are greater than actual years worked while participating in the SERP
is $1,212,131 for Mr.&nbsp;Laderman. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
benefit under the SERP is defined as a single life annuity, which is (a)&nbsp;times (b)&nbsp;minus (c), where: </FONT></P>

<UL>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>(a)</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>is
2.50% of final average compensation;
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>(b)</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>is
credited service; and
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>(c)</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>is
the benefit payable from the CARP. </FONT></DD></DL>
</UL>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
Company will increase the amount for the executive's portion of any Medicare payroll tax incurred in connection with the SERP payout (plus income taxes on such indemnity payment).
This Medicare tax indemnity is expected to be paid in the year the executive terminates. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Normal
retirement under the SERP is age 60, but an officer is entitled to receive a reduced benefit upon the earlier of attaining age 55 or completing 10&nbsp;years of actual service
under the SERP. The benefit is payable as a lump sum, which is the actuarial equivalent of the single life annuity benefit payable at age 60. The lump sum is calculated using the same mortality table
disclosed in the footnote to the financial statements for SERP (the Internal Revenue Service ("IRS") prescribed 417(e) table). It is also calculated using an interest rate that is the average of the
Moody's Aa Corporate Bond rate for the three-month period ending on the last day of the second month preceding payment. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2><A HREF="#bg18001a_main_toc">Table of Contents</A></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=4><A NAME="dy18001_potential_payments_upo__dy102395"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_dy18001_2"> </A>
    </font></p>    <div style="margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:12pt;margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;text-align:left;">    <div style="display:inline-block;*display:inline;zoom:1;box-sizing:border-box;width:100%;">    <table width="100%" border=0
    cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>    <TR bgcolor="#FFFFFF">    <td style="font-family:arial;text-align:left;vertical-align:top;padding-top:3pt;border-top:solid #3255A4 1.0pt;"><p style="font-family:arial;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;;margin-left:15.0pt;text-indent:-15.0pt;">



<!-- COMMAND=ADD_ROWSHADECOLOR,"#FFFFFF" -->





<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:15.0pt;text-indent:-15.0pt;" -->


  <FONT COLOR="#3255A4" SIZE=4>Potential Payments upon Termination or Change in Control</FONT> <FONT SIZE=2></font>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>
</div>
 <P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;This
section quantifies and describes potential payments that may be made to our named executive officers upon termination of employment or upon a change in control of
the Company assuming that such event had occurred on December&nbsp;31, 2019. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;This
section does not include payments for awards that already were earned or vested as of December&nbsp;31, 2019, including (i)&nbsp;the 2019 AIP awards and (ii)&nbsp;long-term
incentive awards granted in 2017 for the 2017-2019 performance period. The 2019 AIP awards are included above under the Non-Equity Incentive Plan Compensation column of the 2019 Summary Compensation
Table and the 2017 Performance-Based RSUs for the 2017-2019 performance period are included in the Option Exercises and Stock Vested for 2019 table. </FONT></P>

<UL>

<P style="font-family:arial;;margin-left:10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>


<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;" -->


Termination Benefits of Mr.&nbsp;Munoz; CEO Transition Agreement  </I></B></FONT></P>

</UL>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;As described in the CD&amp;A above, Mr.&nbsp;Munoz will transition from the role of CEO following the Annual Meeting and will assume the role of
Executive Chairman. In connection with the transition, the Company entered into the Transition Agreement with Mr.&nbsp;Munoz to reflect the terms and conditions of the transition and
Mr.&nbsp;Munoz's continued employment as Executive Chairman. As of December&nbsp;31, 2019, and continuing through the Annual Meeting, Mr.&nbsp;Munoz's employment continues to be governed by the
terms and conditions of his existing Employment Agreement and the table below reflects those benefits as of December&nbsp;31, 2019. For further information related to the terms and conditions of the
Transition Agreement, see "CD&amp;A&#151;CEO Transition Arrangements" above. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pursuant
to the terms of the Employment Agreement, if Mr.&nbsp;Munoz's employment is terminated by the Company without "cause" or if he resigns with "good reason," then
Mr.&nbsp;Munoz will be entitled to certain payments and benefits, including the following: a cash severance payment of $7.5&nbsp;million (representing two times his base salary plus target bonus);
pro-rata payment of his annual bonus for the year of termination based on actual achievement of performance targets; and continuation of welfare benefits for two years. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
Company's incentive awards also specify certain separation benefits and obligations. See "&#151;Termination Due to Death or Disability," "&#151;Involuntary Termination
Without 'Cause' or Voluntary Termination for 'Good Reason'," and "&#151;Change in Control" below for a description of the impact of termination on Mr.&nbsp;Munoz's outstanding incentive
awards. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr.&nbsp;Munoz
is bound by certain non-solicitation and non-competition restrictions during the term of his employment and for a period of one year thereafter. Upon separation,
Mr.&nbsp;Munoz retains lifetime flight benefits and a related tax indemnification, which benefits he retains from his prior service as a non-employee director of the Company. As of
December&nbsp;31, 2019, Mr.&nbsp;Munoz was not retirement eligible and a change in </FONT></P>
 <font color="??????" style="display:none;">&#8203;</font>

 <DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>(1)</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>No
benefits are changed or enhanced upon a change in control without a qualifying termination event. </FONT></DD></DL>
 </DIV>
 <P style="font-family:arial;;margin-left:10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><FONT SIZE=2><A NAME="dy18001_termination_benefits_under_the__ter03132"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_dy18001_3"> </A></FONT> <FONT SIZE=2><B><I>


<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;" -->


Termination Benefits under the Executive Severance Plans and Award Agreements    <BR>    </I></B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;As of December&nbsp;31, 2019, Messrs.&nbsp;Kirby, G. Hart, B. Hart and Laderman were eligible for termination benefits pursuant to the
Company's Executive Severance Plan. The Company's incentive awards also specify benefits and obligations under certain separation scenarios. Below is a narrative description of potential payments to
our named executive officers upon the following separation scenarios:</FONT></P>

<UL>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2> termination for "cause," </FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2> retirement (if eligible) or resignation without "good reason," </FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT
SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2> termination due to death or disability, </FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2> involuntary termination without "cause" or voluntary termination for "good reason," and
</FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2> a change in control. </FONT></DD></DL>
</UL>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;A
tabular summary of the estimated payments and benefits for each of these officers as of December&nbsp;31, 2019 is set forth below the narrative descriptions of these scenarios. As
of December&nbsp;31, 2019, Messrs.&nbsp;G. Hart and Laderman were eligible to retire. </FONT></P>

<UL>

<P style="font-family:arial;;margin-left:10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>


<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;" -->


Termination for "Cause"  </I></B></FONT></P>

</UL>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Upon a termination for "cause," our named executive officers are not entitled to any additional payments or benefits. However, upon any
termination of employment, including a termination for "cause," Mr.&nbsp;Laderman would retain his frozen SERP benefits.  </FONT></P>

<UL>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I> Frozen SERP benefits.</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;The value
of the frozen SERP benefits as of December&nbsp;31, 2019 is set forth in the 2019 Pension Benefits Table and the benefits are described under "Narrative to Pension Benefits Table." This is a frozen
benefit and there is no enhancement of this benefit under any separation scenario. The SERP benefit payable is not affected by the cause of termination, other than death. Assuming a termination on
December&nbsp;31, 2019 other than due to death, the lump sum benefit payable to Mr.&nbsp;Laderman would have been $4,807,520 (payable on </FONT></DD></DL>
</UL>

<UL>
<UL>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>July&nbsp;1,
2020). Assuming a termination on December&nbsp;31, 2019 due to death, the lump sum benefit would have been $2,156,637, payable to the surviving spouse on January&nbsp;1, 2020. For
purposes of these calculations, we assumed that the lump sum interest rate in effect at the time of payment for benefits payable after January&nbsp;1, 2020 will be the same as the assumption
currently in effect (3.14%). For the lump sum mortality assumption, we used the 2020 IRS prescribed 417(e) table. </FONT></P>

</UL>

<P style="font-family:arial;;margin-left:10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>


<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;" -->


Retirement or Resignation without "Good Reason"  </I></B></FONT></P>

</UL>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Messrs.&nbsp;G. Hart and Laderman were retirement eligible on December&nbsp;31, 2019 and were entitled to the retirement benefits described
below. Such benefits are in addition to the frozen SERP benefit of Mr.&nbsp;Laderman described above. Messrs.&nbsp;Munoz, Kirby and B. Hart were not retirement eligible as of December&nbsp;31,
2019 and therefore voluntary separation would be treated as resignation without "good reason" (as defined in the Executive Severance Plan or, in the case of Mr.&nbsp;Munoz, his employment
agreement). The only separation benefit provided to Messrs.&nbsp;Munoz and B. Hart in such circumstances would be lifetime flight benefits, including for Mr.&nbsp;Munoz the grandfathered tax
indemnification on such benefits. Mr.&nbsp;Kirby was not eligible for lifetime flight benefits as of December&nbsp;31, 2019 because such benefits require five years of Company service. </FONT></P>

<UL>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I> Relative Pre-tax Margin Performance-Based
RSUs.</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;Retirement eligible participants receive payments (pro-rata through the retirement date) under the relative pre-tax margin
Performance-Based RSUs if and when actively employed participants receive payments based on the Company's actual performance results through the end of the performance period. The performance period
for the 2018 awards ends on December&nbsp;31, 2020 and the performance period for the 2019 awards ends on December&nbsp;31, 2021. Assuming retirement at December&nbsp;31, 2019, Messrs.&nbsp;G.
Hart and Laderman each would be eligible for payment of (i)&nbsp;two-thirds of the 2018 awards based on the Company's actual performance achieved through December&nbsp;31, 2020 and
(ii)&nbsp;one-third of the 2019 awards based on the Company's actual performance achieved through December&nbsp;31, 2021. </FONT></DD></DL>
</UL>
<UL>
<UL>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>As
an estimate of the future payments to Messrs.&nbsp;G. Hart and Laderman, the termination tables set forth below include (i)&nbsp;two-thirds of the estimated value of the 2018 relative pre-tax
margin Performance-Based RSUs assuming the awards meet the stretch level of performance and (ii)&nbsp;one-third of the estimated value of the 2019 relative pre-tax margin Performance-Based RSUs
assuming the awards meet the stretch level of performance. These calculations are based on the estimates used in the Outstanding Equity Awards at 2019 Fiscal Year-End table and the closing price per
share of Common Stock on December&nbsp;31, 2019 ($88.09). Subject to achievement of the specified performance conditions, the 2019 Performance-Based RSUs are settled in stock and the 2018
Performance-Based RSUs are cash-settled based on the average closing price per share of Common Stock for the 20 trading days immediately preceding the end of the performance period. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>No
amounts are payable under the Performance-Based RSU awards upon a voluntary resignation without "good reason" and therefore no amounts have been included for these awards under this scenario for
Messrs.&nbsp;Munoz, Kirby and B. Hart.  </FONT></P>

</UL>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I> Time-vested RSUs.</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;The time-vested
RSUs granted to Messrs.&nbsp;G. Hart and Laderman vest on a pro-rata basis with respect to the portion of the award scheduled to vest on the next vesting date and the remainder of the time-vested
RSUs are forfeited. The estimated retirement benefit amounts shown in the separation tables for Messrs.&nbsp;G. Hart and Laderman were calculated based on one-third of the value of such awards
included in the Outstanding Equity Awards at 2019 Fiscal Year-End table, which represents the portion of the awards which vested on February&nbsp;28, 2020. </FONT></DD></DL>
</UL>

<!-- ZEQ.=5,SEQ=77,EFW="2241177",CP="UNITED AIRLINES HOLDINGS, INC.",DN="1",CHK=1021836,FOLIO='72',FILE='DISK104:[20ZAD1.20ZAD18001]DY18001A.;20',USER='DCOMBA',CD=';9-APR-2020;08:12' -->
<A NAME="page_dy18001_1_73"> </A>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2><A HREF="#bg18001a_main_toc">Table of Contents</A></FONT></P>

<UL>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I> Stock Options.</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;The unvested stock
options held by Messrs.&nbsp;Kirby and B. Hart terminate upon resignation without "good reason." Messrs.&nbsp;Kirby and B. Hart are the only named executive officers who held unvested stock
options on December&nbsp;31, 2019.  </FONT> <FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I> Continuation Coverage
Benefits.</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;Upon any termination other than for "cause," Mr.&nbsp;Laderman is eligible to receive continued coverage under the Company's health
and welfare benefit plans for himself and his eligible dependents at rates equivalent to those paid by similarly-situated employees who continue in service until he is eligible for Medicare (but in no
event beyond age 65). This benefit was preserved from the terms of Mr.&nbsp;Laderman's pre-merger employment agreement. The remaining named executive officers do not have post-separation
continuation coverage benefits upon retirement or voluntary resignation without "good reason."  </FONT> <FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I> Flight Benefits.</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;Upon any
termination other than for "cause," flight benefits are provided for Messrs.&nbsp;Munoz, G. Hart, B. Hart and Laderman for the remainder of the executive's lifetime, subject to an annual limit. The
Company previously adopted a policy to eliminate tax indemnification for post-separation perquisites, however Messrs.&nbsp;Munoz and Laderman had grandfathered rights to post-separation tax
reimbursements. Upon death, certain executive's survivors will receive a limited flight benefit. For purposes of the tables below this has not been separately valued and is shown for each executive at
the same value as the other termination scenarios. Mr.&nbsp;Kirby was not eligible for lifetime flight benefits as of December&nbsp;31, 2019, which benefits require five years of Company service. </FONT></DD></DL>
</UL>
<UL>

<P style="font-family:arial;;margin-left:10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>


<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;" -->


Termination Due to Death or Disability  </I></B></FONT></P>

</UL>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;If a named executive officer terminated employment due to death or disability on December&nbsp;31, 2019, in addition to applicable benefits
as described above, he would have been entitled to the following benefits: </FONT></P>

<UL>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I> Relative Pre-tax Margin Performance Based
RSUs.</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;Upon death or disability, the 2018 and 2019 pre-tax margin Performance-Based RSU awards vest at the target level and are paid out
immediately on a pro-rata basis. As an estimate of the payment to the named executive officers in the termination tables set forth below, (i)&nbsp;two-thirds of the target opportunity under the 2018
awards has been included and (ii)&nbsp;one-third of the target opportunity under the 2019 awards has been included. </FONT></DD></DL>
</UL>
<UL>
<UL>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
estimated payout value of the 2018 and 2019 Performance-Based RSUs was determined based on the closing price per share of Common Stock on December&nbsp;31, 2019 ($88.09). The 2019
Performance-Based RSUs are settled in stock and the 2018 Performance-Based RSUs are cash-settled based on the average closing price per share of Common Stock for the 20 trading days immediately
preceding the end of the performance period. The pre-tax margin Performance-Based RSU awards outstanding at December&nbsp;31, 2019 are set forth in the Outstanding Equity Awards at 2019 Fiscal
Year-End table based on the stretch level of performance.  </FONT></P>

</UL>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I> Time-Vested RSUs.</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;The time-vested
RSU awards vest in full upon death or disability. The value of each time vested RSU was estimated based on the closing price of a share of Common Stock on December&nbsp;31, 2019 ($88.09 per share). </FONT> <FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I> Stock Options.</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;Outstanding
unvested stock options vest in full upon death or disability. Messrs.&nbsp;Kirby and B. Hart are the only named executive officers who held unvested stock options on December&nbsp;31, 2019. The
value, if any, of the acceleration of vesting of the unexercisable stock options was estimated based on the difference between the applicable option exercise price and the closing price of a share of
Common Stock on December&nbsp;31, 2019 ($88.09 per share). </FONT></DD></DL>
</UL>

<!-- ZEQ.=6,SEQ=78,EFW="2241177",CP="UNITED AIRLINES HOLDINGS, INC.",DN="1",CHK=425598,FOLIO='73',FILE='DISK104:[20ZAD1.20ZAD18001]DY18001A.;20',USER='DCOMBA',CD=';9-APR-2020;08:12' -->
<A NAME="page_dy18001_1_74"> </A>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2><A HREF="#bg18001a_main_toc">Table of Contents</A></FONT></P>

<UL>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I> Continuation Coverage
Benefits.</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;In the case of death, the named executive officers' beneficiaries are entitled to receive proceeds of life insurance benefits equal to
three times base salary (up to a maximum of $3&nbsp;million) at the time of death. In the case of disability, the named executive officer is eligible to receive monthly benefits under the Company's
applicable disability policies. There is no additional cost to the Company associated with payments under these disability policies and therefore no additional amounts are included in the tables with
respect to these policies. </FONT></DD></DL>
</UL>
<UL>

<P style="font-family:arial;;margin-left:10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>


<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;" -->


Involuntary Termination Without "Cause" or Voluntary Termination for "Good Reason"  </I></B></FONT></P>

</UL>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;If any of the named executive officers was terminated by the Company without "cause" or terminated voluntarily for "good reason" (as defined in
the Company's Executive Severance Plan) on December&nbsp;31, 2019, in addition to the applicable benefits described above, he would have been entitled to the following: </FONT></P>

<UL>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I> Cash Severance.</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;Under the
Executive Severance Plan, the named executive officers would receive a cash severance payment equal to two times the sum of his (i)&nbsp;base salary (Kirby&#151;$875,000, G.
Hart&#151;$850,000, B. Hart&#151;$775,000, and Laderman&#151;$725,000) and (ii)&nbsp;AIP target bonus percentage (Kirby&#151;125%, G. Hart&#151;106%, B.
Hart&#151;106%, and Laderman&#151;106% of base salary) multiplied by year-end base salary. </FONT></DD></DL>
</UL>
<UL>
<UL>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
estimated severance payments included in the tables are calculated using the target opportunity percentages referenced above which were in effect as of December&nbsp;31, 2019. However, in an
actual separation event, if the officer was expected to be a named executive officer for the year of termination, then the Executive Severance Plan specifies that the payment calculation uses the
target opportunity percentage that was applicable in the year prior to the separation event. To the extent permitted under Section&nbsp;409A of the Code, the severance payment is made in one lump
sum payment and, if the payment is subject to a six-month delay, interest will be paid on the delayed payment.  </FONT></P>

</UL>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I> Relative Pre-tax Margin Performance Based
RSUs.</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;Upon an involuntary termination without cause or voluntary termination for good reason, Messrs.&nbsp;G. Hart and Laderman would receive
payment for the pre-tax margin Performance Based RSUs based on their retirement eligibility described above. For Messrs.&nbsp;Munoz, Kirby and B. Hart, such awards would be forfeited. </FONT> <FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I> Time-vested RSUs.</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>
&nbsp;&nbsp;Messrs.&nbsp;G. Hart and Laderman would receive payment for a pro-rata portion of the time-vested RSUs scheduled to vest on the next vesting date as described above. The remaining
time-vested RSUs held by the named executive officers would be forfeited.  </FONT> <FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I> Stock Options.</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;Unvested stock
options would be forfeited, except as described below in situations involving a change in control.  </FONT> <FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I> Continuation Coverage
Benefits.</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr.&nbsp;Laderman would receive continued coverage under the Company's health and welfare benefits plans and continued life insurance
benefits as set forth above. Each of the other named executive officers is eligible for continued coverage under the Company's welfare benefit plans for themselves and their eligible dependents and
continued life insurance for 24&nbsp;months following termination (until December&nbsp;31, 2021) or, if earlier, until he receives similar benefits from a subsequent employer. The continuation
coverage benefits require the executives to pay for the benefits at rates equivalent to those paid by similarly situated employees who continue in service and are subject to any Medicare or other
coordination of benefits provisions under the applicable welfare benefit plan. </FONT></DD></DL>
</UL>

<!-- ZEQ.=7,SEQ=79,EFW="2241177",CP="UNITED AIRLINES HOLDINGS, INC.",DN="1",CHK=244602,FOLIO='74',FILE='DISK104:[20ZAD1.20ZAD18001]DY18001A.;20',USER='DCOMBA',CD=';9-APR-2020;08:12' -->
<A NAME="page_dy18001_1_75"> </A>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2><A HREF="#bg18001a_main_toc">Table of Contents</A></FONT></P>

<UL>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I> Outplacement Services.</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>
&nbsp;&nbsp;Outplacement consulting services are provided for 12&nbsp;months following termination. The estimated cost set forth in the tables below is based on our current contracted rates and
officer position. </FONT></DD></DL>
</UL>

<P style="font-family:arial;;margin-left:10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><FONT SIZE=2><A NAME="dy18001__change_in_control_"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_dy18001_4"> </A></FONT> <FONT SIZE=2><B><I>


<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;" -->


"Change in Control"    <BR>    </I></B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;If a "change in control" of the Company had occurred on December&nbsp;31, 2019, generally no payments or benefits would have been provided to
the named executive officers unless there were also a qualifying termination of employment or as noted below. A "qualifying termination" includes involuntary termination without "cause" and voluntary
termination for "good reason". These payments and benefits are generally the same as those provided upon a qualifying termination without a change in control. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
outstanding time-vested RSU awards include a double-trigger with respect to a change in control, with vesting accelerated only if the holder terminates for "good reason" or upon a
qualifying termination within two years of the change in control. The outstanding Performance-Based RSU awards also include double-trigger provisions and upon such trigger the performance goals would
be deemed satisfied at the target level. Payments would require continued employment through the end of the performance period except in situations involving a qualifying termination event, death or
disability. To satisfy requirements of Section&nbsp;409A of the Code, a retirement eligible holder of Performance-Based RSUs would be eligible for an annual pro-rata payment. Payments with respect
to the 2018 and 2019 Performance-Based RSUs would be made on a pro-rated basis upon a qualifying termination event, death or disability. The sign-on stock option awards granted to Mr.&nbsp;Kirby
(which have an exercise price that was set 25% higher than the closing price on the date of grant) would vest upon a change in control without a separate termination event. The stock option awards
granted to Mr.&nbsp;Kirby in connection with the CEO transition and the stock options held by Mr.&nbsp;Hart would only accelerate vesting if such executive experiences a qualifying termination
within two years following a change in control. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;None
of our named executive officers will be entitled to indemnification with respect to excise taxes under Section&nbsp;4999 of the Code for a change in control. Instead, payments
that would be subject to the excise tax will be reduced to the level at which the excise tax will not be applied unless the executive would be in a better net after-tax position by receiving the full
payments and paying the excise tax. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:arial;;margin-left:10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><FONT SIZE=2><A NAME="dy18001_material_defined_terms"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_dy18001_5"> </A></FONT> <FONT SIZE=2><B><I>


<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;" -->


Material Defined Terms    <BR>    </I></B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The terms "cause" and "good reason" as used above are defined under Mr.&nbsp;Munoz's employment agreement, as amended, and the Executive
Severance Plan with respect to the remaining named executive officers and are set forth below. </FONT></P>

<UL>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>"Cause"</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> means, in general, (i)&nbsp;gross neglect or willful gross misconduct;
(ii)&nbsp;conviction of, or plea of nolo contendere to, a felony or crime involving moral turpitude; (iii)&nbsp;the executive's commission of an act of deceit or fraud intended to result in
personal and unauthorized enrichment of the executive at the Company's expense; (iv)&nbsp;a material breach of a material obligation of the executive under the Company's Bylaws or pursuant to any
award or agreement with the executive; (v)&nbsp;the executive's abuse of alcohol or drugs rendering the executive unable to perform the material duties and services required by his position; or
(vi)&nbsp;a material violation of Company policies. </FONT><FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>"Good Reason"</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> means, in general, (i)&nbsp;a material diminution in the executive's authority,
duty or responsibilities; (ii)&nbsp;a material diminution in the executive's base salary, except as part of an across-the-board reduction in salary; (iii)&nbsp;a relocation of the executive's
principal place of employment by more than 50 miles; or (iv)&nbsp;a material breach by the Company of the Executive Severance Plan or, in the case of Mr.&nbsp;Munoz, employment agreement. With
respect to Mr.&nbsp;Munoz, "good reason" also means the failure of any successor or assignee of the Company to assume his employment agreement. </FONT></DD></DL>
</UL>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2><A HREF="#bg18001a_main_toc">Table of Contents</A> </FONT></P>

<UL>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>"Change in Control</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>" means, in general, the occurrence of any one of the following events:
(i)&nbsp;certain acquisitions by a third-party or third-parties, acting in concert, of at least a specified threshold percentage of the Company's then outstanding voting securities;
(ii)&nbsp;consummation of certain mergers or consolidations of the Company with any other corporation; (iii)&nbsp;stockholder approval of a plan of complete liquidation or dissolution of the
Company; (iv)&nbsp;consummation of certain sales or dispositions of all or substantially all the assets of the Company; or (v)&nbsp;certain changes in the membership of the Company's board of
directors. </FONT></DD></DL>
</UL>

<P style="font-family:arial;;margin-left:10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><FONT SIZE=2><A NAME="ea18001_restrictive_covenants_and_release_requirement"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_ea18001_1"> </A></FONT> <FONT SIZE=2><B><I>


<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;" -->


Restrictive Covenants and Release Requirement    <BR>    </I></B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Our restricted share awards and time-vested RSU awards include restrictive covenants related to non-solicitation, non-competition and no-hire
provisions for a period of one year following termination of employment (except, with respect to the non-competition covenant, if such termination is an involuntary termination by the Company without
"cause" or by the executive for "good reason"). Similar restrictive covenants apply under the employment agreement of Mr.&nbsp;Munoz, under the terms of the stock option award granted to
Mr.&nbsp;Kirby in 2019, and pursuant to surviving obligations under the prior employment agreements between the Company and Messrs.&nbsp;G. Hart, B. Hart and Laderman. In addition, each of the
officers is bound by an obligation of confidentiality for an indefinite duration. The Company's Executive Severance Plan and Mr.&nbsp;Munoz's employment agreement contain a requirement to execute a
release of claims in favor of the Company to receive the separation benefits described herein. </FONT></P>
 <div style="display:none;*display:block;margin-top:-1pt;"></div>

at December&nbsp;31, 2019.

benefits are changed or enhanced upon a change in control without a qualifying termination event. </FONT></DD></DL>

 <DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>(1)</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
time-vested RSUs and the Performance-Based RSUs award would be paid in accordance with the retirement separation based on Mr.&nbsp;Laderman's retirement
eligibility at December&nbsp;31, 2019.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>(2)</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>No
benefits are changed or enhanced upon a change in control without a qualifying termination event. </FONT></DD></DL>
 </DIV>
 <P style="font-family:arial;;margin-left:10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><FONT SIZE=2><A NAME="ea18001_methodologies_and_assumptions___met03783"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_ea18001_2"> </A></FONT> <FONT SIZE=2><B><I>


<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;" -->


Methodologies and Assumptions used for Calculating Other Potential Post-Employment Payments    <BR>    </I></B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;For purposes of quantifying the payments and estimated benefits disclosed in the foregoing tables, the Company utilized the following
assumptions and methodologies to calculate the applicable costs to the Company: </FONT></P>

<UL>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I> Continuation Coverage
benefits.</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;The expected future present values of medical and prescription drug coverage and life insurance benefits that are continued for a
pre-defined period following certain qualifying triggering events was determined based on assumptions used for financial reporting purposes (i.e.,&nbsp;FASB ASC 715-20-50 assumptions) using a
discount rate of 3.35%. The expected future present values for the continuation coverage benefits were based on 2020 employer gross costs, including employer contributions to the health care savings
and reimbursement accounts less employee contributions based on 2020 coverage elections. The estimates use a health care cost trend related to the medical and prescription drug benefits (including
employer and employee contributions) of 5.8% in 2020, grading down to 4.5% in 2033. The separation scenarios include the portion of the benefits that is greater than the benefit that would be provided
to all management employees. The value of the continued life insurance benefits was calculated using the January 2020 term life insurance cost to the Company of purchasing this coverage and assuming
no cost increase because the premium is not age-related.  </FONT> <FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I> Flight benefits and related tax
reimbursements.</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;The value of lifetime travel privileges was determined by utilizing the following assumptions: (i)&nbsp;executive and eligible
family members and significant others continue to utilize the travel benefit for a period of 20&nbsp;years following termination; (ii)&nbsp;the level of usage for each year is the same as the
actual usage was for the executive and such persons for 2019; and (iii)&nbsp;the incremental cost to the Company for </FONT></DD></DL>
</UL>
 <font color="??????" style="display:none;">&#8203;</font>
 <div style="margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:12pt;">
<div style="display:none;
*display:block;
margin-top:-4pt;
"></div>

position:relative;
width:100%;
margin-left:0%;
">

<div style="width:10.0pt;

<p

<!-- ZEQ.=3,SEQ=83,EFW="2241177",CP="UNITED AIRLINES HOLDINGS, INC.",DN="1",CHK=242074,FOLIO='78',FILE='DISK104:[20ZAD1.20ZAD18001]EA18001A.;17',USER='DCOMBA',CD=';9-APR-2020;08:12' -->
<A NAME="page_ea18001_1_79"> </A>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2><A HREF="#bg18001a_main_toc">Table of Contents</A></FONT></P>

<UL>
<UL>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>providing
travel benefits for each year is the same as the actual incremental cost incurred by the Company for providing travel benefits to the executive and eligible family members and significant
others for 2019. Based on these assumptions, the Company determined the value of lifetime travel benefits by calculating the present value of the assumed incremental cost of providing the benefit to
the executive and the executive's eligible family members over a 20-year period using a discount rate of 3.35%. The tax indemnification on lifetime flight benefits was determined utilizing the same
three assumptions stated above. Using these assumptions, the Company determined the value of the indemnification by calculating the present value of the executive's future assumed annual tax
indemnification (equal to the executive's actual 2019 tax indemnity) over a 20-year period using a discount rate of 3.35%. </FONT></P>

</UL>
</UL>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=4><A NAME="ea18001_2019_ceo_pay_ratio"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_ea18001_3"> </A>
    </font></p>    <div style="margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:12pt;margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;text-align:left;">    <div style="display:inline-block;*display:inline;zoom:1;box-sizing:border-box;width:100%;">    <table width="100%" border=0
    cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>    <TR bgcolor="#FFFFFF">    <td style="font-family:arial;text-align:left;vertical-align:top;padding-top:3pt;border-top:solid #3255A4 1.0pt;"><p style="font-family:arial;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;;margin-left:15.0pt;text-indent:-15.0pt;">



<!-- COMMAND=ADD_ROWSHADECOLOR,"#FFFFFF" -->





<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:15.0pt;text-indent:-15.0pt;" -->


  <FONT COLOR="#3255A4" SIZE=4>2019 CEO Pay Ratio</FONT> <FONT SIZE=2></font>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>
</div>
 <P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;As
required by Section&nbsp;953(b) of the Dodd-Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act and Item&nbsp;402(u) of Regulation&nbsp;S-K, we are providing
information about the relationship of the annual total compensation of our employees and the annual total compensation of our CEO, Oscar Munoz. The CEO pay ratio included below is a reasonable
estimate calculated in a manner consistent with Item&nbsp;402(u) of Regulation&nbsp;S-K. In complying with the CEO pay ratio disclosure requirements, companies are permitted to use a variety of
assumptions and methodologies. As a result, the CEO pay ratio reported by other companies may not be comparable with the ratio reported below since all results are impacted by the nature of each
company's compensation reward structure and employee demographics and the chosen assumptions and methodologies permitted under the SEC rules. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Ratio.</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;For the fiscal year that ended December&nbsp;31, 2019, the estimated median annual total compensation of all
employees of the Company
(including our consolidated subsidiaries, but excluding our CEO) was $74,750 and the 2019 annual total compensation of our CEO was $12,643,005. Based on the foregoing, the 2019 ratio of the annual
total compensation of our CEO to the median of the annual total compensation of all employees is estimated to be 169 to 1. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Identifying the Median Employee and Calculating Total Compensation.</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Since December&nbsp;1, 2018 (the date used to
select the 2018 median
employee), there have not been any changes in the Company's employee population or employee compensation arrangements that we believe would significantly impact the pay ratio disclosure. However,
there were significant changes in the circumstances related to calculation of 2019 annual compensation for the median employee originally identified in 2018 that would result in a significant change
in our pay ratio disclosure if the 2019 compensation of such employee was utilized to calculate our 2019 CEO pay ratio. Therefore, as permitted under the CEO pay ratio disclosure rules, we are using a
previously identified alternate median employee to calculate the 2019 CEO pay ratio. The alternate median employee was identified in the process described below with respect to the original median
employee, and the alternate employee's 2018 compensation was substantially similar to the original median employee based on the compensation measure used to select the original median employee. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;For
purposes of identifying the median employee as of December&nbsp;31, 2018, based on our internal payroll records, we determined that there were approximately 91,700 employees of
the Company (including our consolidated subsidiaries), of which approximately 4,100 were located outside of the United States. Pursuant to the </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>de
minimis</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> exemption provided under Item&nbsp;402(u) of Regulation&nbsp;S-K, because our non-U.S. employees account for less than 5% of our total U.S. and non-U.S. employees,
all our international employees have been excluded. Our Guam employees are included with our U.S. employees for purposes of these calculations. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;As
of December&nbsp;31, 2018, our international employee locations and the number of excluded employees in each location were as follows: Antigua and Barbuda&#151;1;
Argentina&#151;147; Aruba&#151;1; Australia&#151;49; Bahamas&#151;2; Belgium&#151;45; Belize&#151;17; Brazil&#151;322; Canada&#151;19; Cayman
Islands&#151;1; Chile&#151;14; China&#151;161; Colombia&#151;57; Costa Rica&#151;90; Denmark&#151;2; Dominican Republic&#151;32;
Ecuador&#151;33; El Salvador&#151;45; </FONT></P>
 <font color="??????" style="display:none;">&#8203;</font>

    </font></p>    <div style="margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:12pt;margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;text-align:left;">    <div style="display:inline-block;*display:inline;zoom:1;box-sizing:border-box;width:100%;">    <table width="100%" border=0

compensation for Mr.&nbsp;Munoz is shown in the 2019 Summary Compensation Table. For purposes of the disclosure in this section, we refer to the non-employee directors elected by the holders of our
Common Stock as "non-employee directors." </FONT></P>

amount shown in this column represents the grant date fair value of 2,103 restricted share units granted to each of the non-employee directors on May&nbsp;23,
2019 determined in accordance with FASB ACS Topic 718. For Ms.&nbsp;Garvey, the amount shown also includes the grant date fair value of 1,484 restricted share units granted on May&nbsp;23, 2019
for her service as Non-Executive Chairman.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><BR></DT><DD style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>Upon
settlement, the restricted share units generally are structured to be settled: (i)&nbsp;50% in cash, including any fractional share units, based
on the average of the high and low sales prices of Common Stock on the vesting date; and (ii)&nbsp;50% in shares of Common Stock. For those directors who elected to defer their equity award, the
full award is deferred into deferred share units as described below under "&#151;Director Compensation Deferral under the DEIP." With respect to the cash-settled portion of the restricted share
unit award for those directors who have not elected a deferral, the grant date fair value was calculated by </FONT></DD></DL>

 <DIV style="padding:0pt;position:relative;text-align:left;margin-left:17%;">

<UL>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>multiplying
the number of cash-settled units by the average of the high and low trading prices per share of Common Stock on the date of grant ($80.87 per share on May&nbsp;23, 2019). With respect to
the share-settled portion of the restricted share unit award, the grant date fair value was calculated by multiplying the number of share-settled units by the closing price per share of Common Stock
on the date of grant ($80.91 per share on May&nbsp;23, 2019).  </FONT></P>

</UL>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><BR></DT><DD style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>As
of December&nbsp;31, 2019, the aggregate number of share units outstanding (including, as applicable, deferred share units) for each individual who
served as a non-employee director was: 2,103 for each of Mses. Corvi and Hooper and Messrs.&nbsp;Harford and Kennedy; 11,680 for Ms.&nbsp;Garvey; 38,303 for Mr.&nbsp;Isaacson; 6,380 for
Mr.&nbsp;Philip; 11,453 for Messrs.&nbsp;Shapiro and Whitehurst; and 9,131 for Mr.&nbsp;Vitale. Captain Insler, Mr.&nbsp;Pantoja and Mr.&nbsp;Nuti did not hold any outstanding share units as
of December&nbsp;31, 2019.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>(4)</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>All
other compensation includes: (a)&nbsp;with respect to certain directors, matching contributions of up to $20,000 to nonprofit organization(s) to which the
director, or in the case of each of the ALPA director and the IAM director, the director's union, made a contribution(s) (including contributions as follows: $20,000 for each of Ms.&nbsp;Hooper and
Messrs.&nbsp;Harford, Kennedy, Pantoja (IAM), Shapiro, Vitale and Whitehurst; $5,000 for Ms.&nbsp;Corvi; and $15,000 for Ms.&nbsp;Garvey), as discussed under the caption "&#151;Charitable
Contributions" below; (b)&nbsp;a tax reimbursement relating to flight benefits (which value is greater than the incremental cost to the Company of providing such benefits) for each director as
follows: Ms.&nbsp;Corvi&#151;$5,434; Ms.&nbsp;Garvey&#151;$2,130; Mr.&nbsp;Harford&#151;$34,297; Ms.&nbsp;Hooper&#151;$8,572; Captain Insler&#151;$26,188;
Mr.&nbsp;Isaacson&#151;$14,610; Mr.&nbsp;Kennedy&#151;$24,885; Mr.&nbsp;Pantoja&#151;$14,225; Mr.&nbsp;Philip&#151;$16,463; Mr.&nbsp;Shapiro&#151;$31,720;
Mr.&nbsp;Vitale&#151;$8,781; Mr.&nbsp;Whitehurst&#151;$24,401; and Mr.&nbsp;Nuti&#151;$10,524; and (c)&nbsp;as required by SEC rules, the aggregate incremental cost to the
Company of such director's flight benefits.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>(5)</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>Our
directors who are employees of the Company or who are directors elected by a class of stock other than Common Stock do not receive any cash or equity
compensation from the Company related to their service as directors. However, each of the ALPA director and the IAM director are entitled to receive certain travel benefits. See "&#151;Travel
Benefits" below and footnote 4 above. With respect to 2019, Captain Insler and Mr.&nbsp;Pantoja did not receive any director compensation other than the benefits set forth in the "All Other
Compensation" column.  </FONT></DD></DL>
 </DIV>
 <P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
Nominating/Governance Committee periodically reviews and makes recommendations to the Board regarding the form and amount of compensation of the Company's non-employee directors.
The Nominating/Governance Committee has not delegated any authority with respect to director compensation matters, and no executive officer plays a role in determining the amount of director
compensation. The Compensation Committee's independent compensation consultant, Exequity, has advised the Nominating/Governance Committee with respect to director compensation matters. These matters
include, among other things, a review and market analysis of board of director pay and benefits and share ownership guidelines. The Company's non-employee director compensation program was designed
with reference to median director pay levels among the companies that comprise the Company's benchmarking peer group. See "Executive Compensation&#151;Compensation Discussion and
Analysis&#151;Compensation Process and Oversight&#151;Benchmarking" for a listing of the companies included in this group. In connection with such review the annual cash retainer fee for
non-employee directors increased from $85,000 to $100,000 and the equity retainer increased from $160,000 to $170,000, effective in 2019. The compensation for the non-employee directors, including
compensation for the Non-Executive Chairman, was approved by the independent members of the Board upon recommendation of the Nominating/Governance Committee. </FONT></P>

<!-- ZEQ.=2,SEQ=87,EFW="2241177",CP="UNITED AIRLINES HOLDINGS, INC.",DN="1",CHK=790153,FOLIO='82',FILE='DISK104:[20ZAD1.20ZAD18001]EC18001A.;16',USER='CHE108068',CD=';8-APR-2020;02:23' -->
<A NAME="page_ec18001_1_83"> </A>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2><A HREF="#bg18001a_main_toc">Table of Contents</A></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=4><A NAME="ec18001_cash_retainers_for_board_and_committee_service"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_ec18001_2"> </A>
    </font></p>    <div style="margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:12pt;margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;text-align:left;">    <div style="display:inline-block;*display:inline;zoom:1;box-sizing:border-box;width:100%;">    <table width="100%" border=0
    cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>    <TR bgcolor="#FFFFFF">    <td style="font-family:arial;text-align:left;vertical-align:top;padding-top:3pt;border-top:solid #3255A4 1.0pt;"><p style="font-family:arial;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;;margin-left:15.0pt;text-indent:-15.0pt;">



<!-- COMMAND=ADD_ROWSHADECOLOR,"#FFFFFF" -->





<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:15.0pt;text-indent:-15.0pt;" -->


  <FONT COLOR="#3255A4" SIZE=4>Cash Retainers for Board and Committee Service</FONT> <FONT SIZE=2></font>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>
</div>
 <P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In
2019, the Company's non-employee directors received the following cash retainers for Board and committee service:</FONT></P>

<UL>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2> an annual retainer of $100,000; </FONT><FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2> an additional annual retainer of $20,000 for the Chairperson of each of the Compensation, Executive, Finance, Nominating/Governance and Public
Responsibility Committees and an additional annual retainer of $25,000 for the Chairperson of the Audit Committee; and </FONT><FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:arial;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2> an additional annual retainer of $12,500 for each of the members (other than the Chairperson) of the Compensation, Executive, Finance,
Nominating/Governance and Public Responsibility Committees and an additional annual retainer of $15,000 for each of the members (other than the Chairperson) of the Audit Committee. </FONT></DD></DL>
</UL>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In
recognition of the impact of COVID-19 on United's business and to lead by example, the Company's non-employee directors waived 100% of their cash compensation for the second and
third quarters of 2020. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=4><A NAME="ec18001_equity_compensation"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_ec18001_3"> </A>
    </font></p>    <div style="margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:12pt;margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;text-align:left;">    <div style="display:inline-block;*display:inline;zoom:1;box-sizing:border-box;width:100%;">    <table width="100%" border=0
    cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>    <TR bgcolor="#FFFFFF">    <td style="font-family:arial;text-align:left;vertical-align:top;padding-top:3pt;border-top:solid #3255A4 1.0pt;"><p style="font-family:arial;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;;margin-left:15.0pt;text-indent:-15.0pt;">



<!-- COMMAND=ADD_ROWSHADECOLOR,"#FFFFFF" -->





<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:15.0pt;text-indent:-15.0pt;" -->


  <FONT COLOR="#3255A4" SIZE=4>Equity Compensation</FONT> <FONT SIZE=2></font>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>
</div>
 <P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;To
attract and retain the services of experienced and knowledgeable non-employee directors, the Company adopted the 2006 Director Equity Incentive Plan, as amended and
restated on February&nbsp;20, 2014 (the "DEIP"). Under the DEIP, non-employee directors may receive periodic awards, stock compensation and/or cash compensation. Periodic awards are equity-based
awards, including options, restricted stock, stock appreciation rights and/or shares, that are granted to non-employee directors from time to time at the discretion of the Board. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Non-employee
directors currently receive an annual equity award valued at $170,000, which is made in connection with the non-employee directors' election to the Board at the annual
stockholder meeting. The
equity award size is calculated based on the average of the high and low sales prices of Common Stock on the date of grant. The Non-Executive Chairman receives an additional annual equity award, as
described below. In each case, each share unit represents the economic equivalent of one share of Common Stock and vests on the one-year anniversary of the date of grant. Upon settlement, the share
units are designed to be settled: (i)&nbsp;50% in cash based on the average of the high and low trading prices per share of Common Stock on the one-year anniversary date and (ii)&nbsp;50% in
shares of Common Stock. Any fractional units are settled in cash. Pursuant to the terms of the DEIP, a director may elect to receive the cash-settled portion of the award in shares and pursuant to any
applicable deferral election, the award is deferred into a share unit account under the DEIP. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=4><A NAME="ec18001_non-executive_chairman_compensation"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_ec18001_4"> </A>
    </font></p>    <div style="margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:12pt;margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;text-align:left;">    <div style="display:inline-block;*display:inline;zoom:1;box-sizing:border-box;width:100%;">    <table width="100%" border=0
    cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>    <TR bgcolor="#FFFFFF">    <td style="font-family:arial;text-align:left;vertical-align:top;padding-top:3pt;border-top:solid #3255A4 1.0pt;"><p style="font-family:arial;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;;margin-left:15.0pt;text-indent:-15.0pt;">



<!-- COMMAND=ADD_ROWSHADECOLOR,"#FFFFFF" -->





<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:15.0pt;text-indent:-15.0pt;" -->


  <FONT COLOR="#3255A4" SIZE=4>Non-Executive Chairman Compensation</FONT> <FONT SIZE=2></font>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>
</div>
 <P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In
addition to the cash and equity compensation described above, the independent members of the Board has approved additional compensation for the Non-Executive
Chairman of $200,000 annually, of which: (i)&nbsp;$80,000 is paid in four equal quarterly installments and (ii)&nbsp;$120,000 is granted in share units under the DEIP. This compensation has been
in effect since 2015 and remained unchanged for 2019. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;As
discussed elsewhere in this proxy statement, Ms.&nbsp;Garvey is retiring from the Board at the end of her current term. Following the Annual Meeting, Mr.&nbsp;Munoz has been
selected to succeed Ms.&nbsp;Garvey as Executive Chairman of the Board and Mr.&nbsp;Philip has been chosen by the independent members of the Board </FONT></P>
 <font color="??????" style="display:none;">&#8203;</font>

<div style="display:none;

<!-- ZEQ.=3,SEQ=88,EFW="2241177",CP="UNITED AIRLINES HOLDINGS, INC.",DN="1",CHK=935573,FOLIO='83',FILE='DISK104:[20ZAD1.20ZAD18001]EC18001A.;16',USER='CHE108068',CD=';8-APR-2020;02:23' -->
<A NAME="page_ec18001_1_84"> </A>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2><A HREF="#bg18001a_main_toc">Table of Contents</A></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>to
serve as Lead Director. Compensation for the role of Lead Director has not yet been established by the Nominating/Governance Committee. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=4><A NAME="ec18001_director_compensation_deferral_under_the_deip"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_ec18001_5"> </A>
    </font></p>    <div style="margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:12pt;margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;text-align:left;">    <div style="display:inline-block;*display:inline;zoom:1;box-sizing:border-box;width:100%;">    <table width="100%" border=0
    cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>    <TR bgcolor="#FFFFFF">    <td style="font-family:arial;text-align:left;vertical-align:top;padding-top:3pt;border-top:solid #3255A4 1.0pt;"><p style="font-family:arial;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;;margin-left:15.0pt;text-indent:-15.0pt;">



<!-- COMMAND=ADD_ROWSHADECOLOR,"#FFFFFF" -->





<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:15.0pt;text-indent:-15.0pt;" -->


  <FONT COLOR="#3255A4" SIZE=4>Director Compensation Deferral under the DEIP</FONT> <FONT SIZE=2></font>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>
</div>
 <P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Under
the DEIP, non-employee directors may defer the receipt of some or all of their cash compensation through credits to a share account established under the terms
of the DEIP. Non-employee directors may also defer the receipt of shares that would otherwise be issued under an equity compensation award through credits to his or her share account. Unless otherwise
specified by the director at the time of the deferral election, distribution from the share account will be made within 60&nbsp;days following the date on which the non-employee director terminates
his or her position as a director of the Company. Some of our directors also have deferrals in place with respect to compensation that was earned prior to the 2010 merger and these amounts have
different distribution terms. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=4><A NAME="ec18001_stock_ownership_guidelines"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_ec18001_6"> </A>
    </font></p>    <div style="margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:12pt;margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;text-align:left;">    <div style="display:inline-block;*display:inline;zoom:1;box-sizing:border-box;width:100%;">    <table width="100%" border=0
    cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>    <TR bgcolor="#FFFFFF">    <td style="font-family:arial;text-align:left;vertical-align:top;padding-top:3pt;border-top:solid #3255A4 1.0pt;"><p style="font-family:arial;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;;margin-left:15.0pt;text-indent:-15.0pt;">



<!-- COMMAND=ADD_ROWSHADECOLOR,"#FFFFFF" -->





<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:15.0pt;text-indent:-15.0pt;" -->


  <FONT COLOR="#3255A4" SIZE=4>Stock Ownership Guidelines</FONT> <FONT SIZE=2></font>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>
</div>
 <P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
stock ownership guidelines that apply to our non-employee directors encourage our non-employee directors to hold shares of Common Stock or equity-based awards
(including share units and restricted share units) with a fair market value equal to or exceeding five times the annual cash retainer paid to the non-employee directors. The guidelines provide for a
transition period of five years for non-employee directors to achieve the ownership requirement. The Nominating/Governance Committee reviews equity ownership of the non-employee directors annually.
Once a non-employee director is determined to be in compliance with the stock ownership guidelines, the non-employee director will be considered to be in compliance until such time as he or she sells
or otherwise disposes of any of his or her Common Stock, at which time the Nominating/Governance Committee will re-evaluate the non-employee director's compliance with the stock ownership guidelines.
With the exception of Ms.&nbsp;Hooper, who joined the Board in 2018 and will have a transition period of five years to achieve compliance with the stock ownership guidelines, all of the non-employee
directors were in compliance with the guidelines as of the last measurement date. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=4><A NAME="ec18001_travel_benefits"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_ec18001_7"> </A>
    </font></p>    <div style="margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:12pt;margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;text-align:left;">    <div style="display:inline-block;*display:inline;zoom:1;box-sizing:border-box;width:100%;">    <table width="100%" border=0
    cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>    <TR bgcolor="#FFFFFF">    <td style="font-family:arial;text-align:left;vertical-align:top;padding-top:3pt;border-top:solid #3255A4 1.0pt;"><p style="font-family:arial;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;;margin-left:15.0pt;text-indent:-15.0pt;">



<!-- COMMAND=ADD_ROWSHADECOLOR,"#FFFFFF" -->





<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:15.0pt;text-indent:-15.0pt;" -->


  <FONT COLOR="#3255A4" SIZE=4>Travel Benefits</FONT> <FONT SIZE=2></font>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>
</div>
 <P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We
consider it important for our directors to understand our business and to have exposure to our operations and employees. For that reason, our directors receive
flight benefits, including a travel card permitting positive space travel by the director, the director's spouse or qualified domestic partner and certain other eligible travelers, and access to our
United Club facilities. These benefits are taxable to the director, subject to the reimbursement of certain of such taxes by the Company. Prior to the 2010 merger, the Company and Continental adopted
policies to eliminate tax indemnification for post-separation perquisites provided to non-employee directors who did not have an existing right to such benefits as of the date the respective policy
was adopted. The tax indemnification provided to the non-employee directors is subject to an annual limit. A non-employee director who retires from the Board with at least five consecutive years of
service as a director will receive lifetime travel benefits, subject to certain exceptions. In addition, Mr.&nbsp;Pantoja will receive lifetime travel benefits if he meets the required five years of
consecutive service on the Board. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=4><A NAME="ec18001_charitable_contributions"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_ec18001_8"> </A>
    </font></p>    <div style="margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:12pt;margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;text-align:left;">    <div style="display:inline-block;*display:inline;zoom:1;box-sizing:border-box;width:100%;">    <table width="100%" border=0
    cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>    <TR bgcolor="#FFFFFF">    <td style="font-family:arial;text-align:left;vertical-align:top;padding-top:3pt;border-top:solid #3255A4 1.0pt;"><p style="font-family:arial;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;;margin-left:15.0pt;text-indent:-15.0pt;">



<!-- COMMAND=ADD_ROWSHADECOLOR,"#FFFFFF" -->





<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"margin-left:15.0pt;text-indent:-15.0pt;" -->


  <FONT COLOR="#3255A4" SIZE=4>Charitable Contributions</FONT> <FONT SIZE=2></font>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>
</div>
 <P style="font-family:arial;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
Company provides a matching charitable contribution to qualifying nonprofit organizations to which a director makes a personal commitment in an aggregate amount of
up to $20,000 per year. In the case of each of the ALPA director and the IAM director, the Company will provide matching charitable contributions of up to $20,000 per year in the aggregate to
qualifying nonprofit organizations to which either the director or the director's union contributes. During 2019, the Company also donated complimentary positive space air travel to qualified
charitable organizations selected by the non-employee directors. In 2019, such directors were permitted to donate up to four round trip tickets to qualified charitable organizations. </FONT></P>
 <font color="??????" style="display:none;">&#8203;</font>
 <div style="margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:12pt;">
<div style="display:none;
*display:block;
margin-top:-4pt;
"></div>

<p
